The '''Scotland national football team'''<ref group="note">{{langx|gd|Sgioba Ball-coise Nàiseanta na h-Alba}}<br />{{langx|sco|Scotland naitional fitbaw team}}</ref> represents [[Scotland]] in men's international [[Association football|football]] and is controlled by the [[Scottish Football Association]]. They compete in three major professional tournaments: the [[FIFA World Cup]], [[UEFA Nations League]], and the [[UEFA European Championship]]. Scotland, as a [[Countries of the United Kingdom|country of the United Kingdom]], are not a member of the [[International Olympic Committee]] (as Scottish athletes compete for [[Great Britain at the Olympics|Great Britain]]), and therefore the national team does not compete in the [[Olympic Games]]. The majority of [[Scotland national football team home stadium|Scotland's home matches]] are played at the national stadium, [[Hampden Park]].

Scotland are the joint oldest national football team in the world, alongside [[England national football team|England]], whom they played in the world's [[1872 Scotland v England football match|first international football match]] in 1872. Scotland has a long-standing [[England–Scotland football rivalry|rivalry with England]],<ref name="them">{{cite web|url=https://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/special_report/1999/11/99/battle_of_britain/473756.stm|title=A history of fierce football rivalry|date=13 October 1999|access-date=25 October 2007|publisher=BBC|archive-date=15 September 2007|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070915135505/http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/special_report/1999/11/99/battle_of_britain/473756.stm|url-status=live}}</ref> whom they played annually from 1872 until 1989. The teams have met only nine times since then, most recently in a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] in September 2023.

Scotland have qualified for the FIFA World Cup on nine occasions, and the UEFA European Championship four times, but they have never progressed beyond the first group stage of a finals tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2021-06-22|title=Modric magic ensures Croatia prolong Scotland's tournament woes|url=https://www.espn.com/soccer/uefa-european-championship/story/4417211/modric-magic-ensures-croatia-prolong-scotlands-major-tournament-woes-as-tartan-armys-euro-2020-hopes-end|access-date=2021-06-23|website=ESPN.com|language=en|archive-date=7 May 2022|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220507010906/https://www.espn.com/soccer/uefa-european-championship/story/4417211/modric-magic-ensures-croatia-prolong-scotlands-major-tournament-woes-as-tartan-armys-euro-2020-hopes-end|url-status=live}}</ref> The team have achieved some noteworthy results, such as beating the [[1966 FIFA World Cup]] winners England 3–2 at [[Wembley Stadium (1923)|Wembley Stadium]] in 1967. [[Archie Gemmill]] scored what has been described as one of the greatest World Cup goals ever in a 3–2 win during the [[1978 FIFA World Cup|1978 World Cup]] against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], who reached the final of the tournament.<ref name="MacLeod" /> In their [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying Group B|qualifying group]] for [[UEFA Euro 2008]], Scotland defeated [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] runners-up [[France national football team|France]] 1–0 in both fixtures.

Scotland supporters are collectively known as the [[Tartan Army]]. The Scottish Football Association operates a [[Scottish FA International Roll of Honour|roll of honour]] for every player who has made more than 50 [[cap (sport)|appearances]] for Scotland.<ref name="roll of honour" /> [[Kenny Dalglish]] holds the record for Scotland appearances, having played 102 times between 1971 and 1986.<ref name="roll of honour" /> Dalglish scored 30 goals for Scotland and shares the record for most goals scored with [[Denis Law]].